included.description:
While supporting a variety of departments and teams at T-Mobile, I:
- Inform design of new solutions via ethnography and contextual inquiry
- Eliminate usability issues in designs by planning and conducting iterative testing with users
- Identify the pain points within existing software by conducting quantitative usability studies
- Gather user feedback on the products by conducting SUS and USE surveys
- Engage multidisciplinary stakeholders (marketing, product management, software engineering professionals) in user research via compelling reports, videos and infographics
- Efficiently provide research services to multiple product teams, and vendors, delivering high-quality deliverables on schedule.
included.title: User Experience Researcher

included.description:

included.description:

Supervisors: Brett Burnside (User Researcher), Brian McCormack (Lead UX Designer)
â¢ Conduct formative research: identify customer pain points by interviewing 11 beginner and experienced Kinesis users in the Amazon lab
â¢ Employ user feedback to develop personas and user journeys
â¢ Redesign Kinesis entry points that allow to collect, store and analyze streaming data in a way that it meets the needs of beginner Kinesis users, validate the prototype through user testing
â¢ Refine the design in InVision and present the final product along with the design rationale to the AWS team
â¢ Develop and validate with the AWS sponsor work plans, interview scripts, prototypes

included.description:
Goal: Utilize a series of user-centered design methods to develop a prototype of an in-store application helping QFC Wallingford customers make healthy food choices
â¢ Performed a series of contextual observations and in-person unstructured interviews with shoppers at QFC Wallingford
â¢ Utilized flow and cultural models (contextual design modeling) to analyze and accurately represent the problem setting
â¢ Created a persona and a problem scenario surfacing the needs of QFC Wallingford customers
â¢ Developed the functional requirements for the system that would resolve the problem
â¢ Used Envisioning Cards to stimulate and enhance the design process
â¢ Designed a low-fidelity prototype that satisfied the functional requirements
â¢ Developed a usability test plan, which was later tested with 3 potential users of the interactive system
â¢ Drafted an effective project proposal documenting every step of the development process

â¢ Performed user needs analysis by recruiting and conducting in-person interviews with potential users
â¢ Following analysis of the qualitative data, developed personas indicating frustrations, desires and needs of prospective adoptive parents interested in adopting a Chinese child

included.description:
Goal: Designed, piloted and analyzed the study titled "The Effect of the University Book Store Environment on UW iSchool Graduate Students' Textbook Purchasing Habits"
Intrigued about the decline of students' interest in purchasing books at the University of Washington Book Store, we reviewed recent research focusing on the students' textbook purchasing habits. Unsatisfied with our results, we developed our own pilot study that explored the relationship between the Book Store environment and students' purchasing behavior. We designed our small-scale pilot study via a survey that collected both quantitative and qualitative data.
included.title: Experimental Research Methods
